A: The problem is that you are reading one byte at a time, which is very inefficient. You should read the entire buffer at once.
Here is a modified version of your code:
byte[] buffer = new byte[1048576];
int i = 0;
int length = -1;

while (true)
{
    int b = is.read(buffer, i, buffer.length - i);
    if (b == -1)
    {
        success = false;
        break;
    }
    i += b;

    if (i == 3)
    {
        length = buffer[0] | buffer[1] << 8 | buffer[2] << 16 | buffer[3] << 24;
        break;
    }
}

This code reads the entire buffer at once, and then processes the bytes as needed. It also updates the index i as it reads, so you don't have to allocate a new array for each read.
Also, you should check if the read operation returns -1 to indicate that the end of the stream has been reached. If it does, you should break out of the loop.
Finally, if the length is determined by the first 4 bytes, you should break out of the loop after determining the length.

