A: You can use a ByteArrayOutputStream to read the entire response into memory, then you can determine the length from the first bytes of the response.
Here is an example:
ByteArrayOutputStream baos = new ByteArrayOutputStream();
byte[] buffer = new byte[1024];
int length;
while ((length = is.read(buffer)) != -1) {
    baos.write(buffer, 0, length);
}
byte[] response = baos.toByteArray();

// Now you can determine the length from the first bytes of the response
int responseLength = response[0] | (response[1] << 8) | (response[2] << 16) | (response[3] << 24);

This way, you don't need to read the entire response into memory at once, which can be a problem if the response is very large. Instead, you read it in chunks and store it in a ByteArrayOutputStream, which can handle arbitrarily large amounts of data.

